            <h3>Taj Mahal - The Icon of Eternal Love</h3>
            <h4>Overview</h4>
            <p>The Taj Mahal, located on the southern bank of the Yamuna River in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, is one of the most iconic and universally admired masterpieces of the world's heritage. This breathtaking white marble mausoleum was commissioned by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in 1632, in memory of his favorite wife, Mumtaz Mahal, who died during childbirth. The Taj Mahal is not just a symbol of Shah Jahan's eternal love for Mumtaz Mahal but also an embodiment of the grandeur and artistic excellence of the Mughal era.</p>

            <h4>History and Significance</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Earlier History:</strong> The Taj Mahal was commissioned by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in 1632 as a mausoleum for his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal. The construction took approximately 21 years, concluding in 1653. This monument was built on the southern bank of the Yamuna River in Agra and reflects the profound love Shah Jahan had for Mumtaz Mahal.</li>
                <li><strong>Architectural Significance:</strong> The Taj Mahal is celebrated for its breathtaking beauty and intricate design. The central dome is 73 meters high and is surrounded by four minarets. The mausoleum is constructed of white marble inlaid with precious stones, featuring elaborate floral patterns and calligraphy. The layout includes a vast garden divided into four parts by waterways, which exemplifies Mughal Garden design.</li>
                <li><strong>UNESCO Recognition:</strong> The Taj Mahal was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983. It is recognized for its outstanding universal value as a masterpiece of Mughal architecture and a symbol of eternal love. Its inclusion highlights its historical importance and architectural excellence.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
